english:
  title: On an Image of Avalokiteshvara
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Avalokiteshvara, the Bodhisattva,
    appears in white robes, pure and luminous—
    like moonlight reflected upon still water.
    The wilted leaves of the lotus root,
    from which the fragrance rises,
    rest in the bamboo grove
    where she sits in perfect peace,
    her empty heart mirrored in all things.

    What does the child attendant seek?
    He kneels, bowing low in reverence.
    If it is the Law he pursues,
    then know that the Law dwells within him too.

    Who is the painter of this image?
    One called Han, they say.
    And Jung drew the bamboo so skillfully
    that their work is now complete.
    I add my words of praise to theirs—
    though I am but a small addition,
    like a wart upon the perfect form.
  footnotes:
    - Avalokiteshvara (Guanyin in Chinese, Gwaneum in Korean) is the Bodhisattva of Compassion in East Asian Buddhism.
    - The lotus root with dried leaves is a traditional symbol in Buddhist iconography, representing the emergence of enlightenment from worldly attachments.
    - The 'child attendant' (dongja) typically represents one of Avalokiteshvara's companions in Buddhist art.
    - The final image comparing himself to 'a wart' is Lee Kyu-bo's modest self-deprecation—a common poetic convention in Classical Chinese and Korean literature when offering praise alongside the work of others.
